# TypeScript Standards

## Strict Mode

TypeScript `strict: true` is required. Never use `any` — use `unknown` and narrow with type guards.

## Typing

- Export interfaces/types from `src/types/` for shared use
- Prefer `interface` for object shapes, `type` for unions/intersections
- Always type function parameters and return values explicitly
- Use `Readonly<T>` for data that should not be mutated

## Error Handling

```typescript
// ❌ BAD: swallowing errors, using `any`
try {
  await doWork();
} catch (e: any) {
  console.log(e.message);
}

// ✅ GOOD: typed errors, proper logging, re-throwing
try {
  await doWork();
} catch (error: unknown) {
  if (error instanceof AppError) {
    logger.error('Operation failed', { code: error.code, message: error.message });
    throw error;
  }
  throw new AppError('Unexpected error', 500, { cause: error });
}
```

## Imports

- Use named exports, not default exports
- Group imports: node built-ins → third-party → project modules
- Use path aliases if configured (e.g., `@/db/queries`)

## Naming

- `camelCase` for variables, functions, methods
- `PascalCase` for interfaces, types, classes, enums
- `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` for constants
- Prefix interfaces with descriptive nouns, not `I` (use `UserPayload`, not `IUser`)
